abstract = {The observed properties of giant planets, models of their evolution, and $\backslash$nobservations of protoplanetary disks provide constraints on the$\backslash$nformation of gas giant planets. The four largest planets in our solar$\backslash$nsystem contain considerable quantities of hydrogen and helium; these$\backslash$ngases could not have condensed into solid planetesimals within the$\backslash$nprotoplanetary disk. Jupiter and Saturn are mostly hydrogen and helium,$\backslash$nbut have larger abundances of heavier elements than does the Sun.$\backslash$nNeptune and Uranus are primarily composed of heavier elements. The$\backslash$ntransiting extrasolar planet HD149026b, which is slightly more massive$\backslash$nthan Saturn, appears to have comparable amounts of light gases and heavy$\backslash$nelements. The other observed transiting exoplanets are primarily$\backslash$nhydrogen and helium, but may contain supersolar abundances of heavy$\backslash$nelements. Spacecraft flybys and observations of satellite orbits provide$\backslash$nestimates of the gravitational moments of the giant planets in our solar$\backslash$nsystem, which in turn provide information on the internal distribution$\backslash$nof matter within Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. Atmospheric$\backslash$nthermal structure and heat flow measurements constrain the interior$\backslash$ntemperatures of these planets. Internal processes may cause giant$\backslash$nplanets to become more compositionally differentiated or alternatively$\backslash$nmore homogeneous; high-pressure laboratory experiments provide data$\backslash$nuseful for modeling these processes. The preponderance of evidence$\backslash$nsupports the core nucleated gas accretion model. According to this$\backslash$nmodel, giant planets begin their growth by the accumulation of small$\backslash$nsolid bodies, as do terrestrial planets. However, unlike terrestrial$\backslash$nplanets, the giant planet cores grow massive 