 of plagioclase fractionation, and $\delta$ 88Sr can be successfully modelled by the heavy isotopes of Sr being preferentially partitioned into plagioclase with a fractionation factor of {\~{}}1.0007 for 88Sr/ 86Sr. Our results demonstrate that Sr stable isotopes may be significantly fractionated at high temperatures and their measurement can provide insights into planetary evolution and magmatic processes. {\textcopyright} 2012 Elsevier B.V..},
